         <section id="abstract" class="article-section article-section--abstract">
          <div id="en_main_abstract" class="article-section__content mainAbstract" lang="en">
           <h2 class="article-section__header">Abstract</h2>
           <p>A homologous series of donor–π–acceptor dyes was synthesized, differing only in the identity of the halogen substituents about the triphenylamine (TPA; donor) portion of each molecule. Each <b>Dye-X</b> (X=F, Cl, Br, and I) was immobilized on a TiO<sub>2</sub> surface to investigate how the halogen substituents affect the reaction between the light-induced charge-separated state, TiO<sub>2</sub>(e<sup>−</sup>)/<b>Dye-X<sup>+</sup></b>, with iodide in solution. Transient absorption spectroscopy showed progressively faster reactivity towards nucleophilic iodide with more polarizable halogen substituents: <b>Dye-F</b> &lt; <b>Dye-Cl</b> &lt; <b>Dye-Br</b> &lt; <b>Dye-I</b>. Given that all other structural and electronic properties for the series are held at parity, with the exception of an increasingly larger electropositive σ-hole on the heavier halogens, the differences in dye regeneration kinetics for <b>Dye-Cl</b>, <b>Dye-Br</b>, and <b>Dye-I</b> are ascribed to the extent of halogen bonding with the nucleophilic solution species.</p>
          </div>
         </section>
         <span id="after-abstract"></span>
         <section class="article-section align-center">
